Pythagorae primum: this division of the soul seems to have been first attributed to Pythagoras by writers such as Posi- donius, cf. Galen, de Plac. Hipp. et Plat. iv p. 425 ; v p. 478 ; Plutarch, Plae. Phil. iv 4. A more correct statement of the Pythagorean view is no doubt that of Diog. L. viii 30 τὴν ἀνθρώπου ψυχὴν διῃρῆσθαι τριχῆ, εἴς τε νοῦν καὶ φρένας καὶ θυμόν. νοῦν μὲν οὖν καὶ θυμὸν εἶναι καὶ ἐν τοῖς ἄλλοις ζῴοις, φρένας δέ μόνον ἐν ἀνθρώπῳ.

For the Platonic division of the soul into two parts, τὸ λογιστικόν and τὸ ἄλο-γον, the latter being subdivided into τὸ θυμοειδές and τὸ ἐπιθυμητικόν, see n. on i 10, 2ο ‘Plato triplicem.‘ The Stoics on the other hand derived all faculties of the soul from the ἡγεμονικόν. of course applies only to those (including Posidonius) who adopted the Platonic division of the soul. With the Stoies tranquillitas was a calm state of the ἡγεμονικόν due to the obedience of the passions and desires to reason; perturbatio was a disordered state of the same ἡγεμονικόν due to a false judgment (κρίσις).
